As most of the international law is made within, or under the auspices of international organisations, it is essential to study also the legal framework and operational mechanisms of these organisations and their contribution to the development of international law. The course provides broad overview of the law of international institutions, e.g. legal mechanisms that give the international institutions the power, international legal personality, treaty-making power, privileges and immunities, legal responsibility of the institutions etc. In addition to the theoretical overview, the decisions of international courts (ICJ, ICC, ECHR) and discussions in commissions and other international foras (ILC, ILA) are also analyzed in order to enhance practical knowledge of the subject.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of the course is to provide an overview of international institutions, their powers and functioning, as well as the rules and legal acts regulating their operation and the responsibilities of international institutions. The course is aimed to broaden students' knowledge about the operation of international institutions, their treaty-making powers and processes and their contributions to the development of international law.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The student who has passed the course is able to: -	Identify the central principles of the law of international institutions -	Define the sources governing the legal personality of international organizations -	Describe the relationship between international organizations and their Member States -	Explain international organization's treaty making processes -	Compare mandates of different international institutions -	Solve hypothetical cases of legal responsibility of international institutions
